    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with **Yordan Alvarez** (71.69) and **Trea Turner** (70.89) anchoring the lineup, representing our highest efficiency plays. **Trea Turner** benefits immensely from the matchup against Pfaadt, where his speed profile is weaponized by the pitcher\u2019s slow delivery (86% SB conversion), compounded by a premium leadoff spot. Meanwhile, **Yordan Alvarez** remains an auto-start despite facing a tough arm in Castillo; his elite xwOBA of .393 and the +8% boost from the number two hole keep his output robust even against high-tier pitching. We are also capitalizing on **Kyle Schwarber** in the same game, whose elite .402 xwOBA and favorable park factors contribute to a strong 65.10 score.\n\nPlatoon advantages are driving several high-floor starts, most notably for **Colt Keith** (64.95) and **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (61.79). **Colt Keith** leverages a +7% platoon boost against Junk to push well above his base, while **Pete Crow-Armstrong** remains a high-upside play due to an aggressive 14% platoon edge against Ashcraft, despite the risk of Ashcraft\u2019s ability to hold runners. The toughest decision of the morning involved the final bench spots, where **Carson Benge** (36.95) and **Victor Scott II** (36.28) were evaluated. **Carson Benge** fell just short of our 40.0 floor due to a negative platoon split against Lopez, while **Victor Scott II**\u2014usually our primary SB engine\u2014is benched because of a combination of a poor matchup against Suarez and the opposing catcher\u2019s elite pop time, which suppresses his projected stolen base efficiency today.\n\nManagement must remain vigilant regarding our \"Lineup Pending\" designations, specifically for **Hyeseong Kim**, **Yordan Alvarez**, **Josh Smith**, and **Christian Yelich**. **Christian Yelich** is the most precarious start, currently sitting at 40.14; should his confirmed spot in the order shift downward or the wind profile change against Griffin, he is the first candidate to be pulled for a bench pivot. We are proceeding with caution on **Junior Caminero** (51.99), as the combination of facing Fried and a negative park factor limits his ceiling, effectively moving him into a secondary tier of production for this rotation.",
